  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "ncyv38r7OC9xfR/Y3DLdBMy4HlM=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:26.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "Sharing with other users does NOT use the per-wallet AES key. Cross-user shares and chat history instead ride Swarm's Access Control Trie (ACT):\n\n- The publisher's Bee node computes `ECDH(publisher_privkey \u00d7 grantee_pubkey)` to derive a per-session key.\n- A third party that only knows public addresses cannot derive the key (classic discrete-log problem).\n- The Bee node handles encrypt/decrypt transparently; the app calls `uploadFile({ act: true, actHistoryAddress, skipEncryption: true })` on send and `downloadFile({ actPublisher, actHistoryAddress, skipDecryption: true })` on receive.\n\nShare manifests and public profiles themselves stay unencrypted \u2014 they serve as discovery indexes so recipients can find what's shared with them. The data those indexes point to is ACT-protected.\n\nThis split matters for threat modeling: a grantee can decrypt what was shared with them, but revoking access means rotating ACT state, not rotating the wallet-derived sync key used for the owner's own operations.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:26.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:26.000Z"
    }
  },
